<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-042-097 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 444 321</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Graphics World  Oct 1991 v14 n10 p56(6).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Terminator 2: a film effects revolution. (raises computer graphicsto major role in film-making)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Sorensen, Peter.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The movie Terminator 2 (T2) is a breakthrough for computergraphics in Hollywood, moving it from a secondary add-on techniqueto a basic tool of the movie-making industry.andP;  Before T2, graphicsspecial effects were considered untried and therefore unreliablefor major effects in big-budget movies.andP;  The company that changedthe perception is the same one that changed the way space shipsfly on the screen - George Lucas' Industrial Light and Magic(ILM).andP;  James Cameron, director of T2, used ILM to create effectsin an earlier film and felt the technology had reached maturity interms of cost, time and effort.andP;  He integrated computer-generatedeffects into the entire movie.andP;  The coordination of live actorswith the computer-generated characters requires perfectsynchronization of live shots with graphics shots, a tediousprocess.andP;  Cameron was able to complete T2 on time and within itsbudget.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Lucasfilm Ltd. Industrial Light and Magic Div. (Innovations).andO;Topic:     EntertainmentComputer graphicsVirtual RealityNew Technique.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andO;Person:    Cameron, James (Production and direction).andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>